The lower-income lender is controlled by the central bank after a 2014 bailout by the regulator due to its weight of bad loans. Its bid to become a competitive bank following a relaunch in 2016 has struggled to gain traction, partly due to the weak economy. “To build a robust and sustainable long-term operating model, African Bank needs to re-establish itself as a reliable and accepted counterparty in the domestic wholesale funding market,” the lender said in a statement. ($1 = R16.64) --Reuters--